# macOS / Swift Coding Conventions

## Platform Target

- Minimum deployment target: macOS 14.0 (Sonoma)
- All new code must compile and run on macOS 14.0+
- Do not use APIs marked as macOS 15+ without `if #available` guard

## SwiftUI-First

- Use SwiftUI for all new views and components
- Use AppKit only when SwiftUI cannot achieve the requirement (e.g., NSToolbar deep customization, NSEvent interception, low-level pasteboard)
- When mixing AppKit, wrap in `NSViewRepresentable` / `NSViewControllerRepresentable`
- Never import AppKit in a file that can be pure SwiftUI

## Concurrency

- Mark all ViewModel classes with `@MainActor`
- Use structured concurrency (`async/await`, `TaskGroup`) over Combine for new code
- Existing Combine pipelines do not need migration unless being modified
- Use `Task { }` to bridge from synchronous to async contexts; never use `DispatchQueue.main.async` in new code
- Cancel tasks explicitly via `task.cancel()` or `.task { }` modifier lifecycle

## Naming

- Follow [Swift API Design Guidelines](https://www.swift.org/documentation/api-design-guidelines/)
- Types: `UpperCamelCase` (e.g., `ScreenCropConverter`)
- Functions / properties: `lowerCamelCase` (e.g., `cropRectInImagePixels`)
- Boolean properties: read as assertions (`isEnabled`, `hasContent`, `canExport`)
- Protocols describing capability: `-able` / `-ible` suffix (e.g., `Exportable`)
- Protocols describing role: noun (e.g., `DataSource`, `Delegate`)

## Error Handling

- Use `do / try / catch` with typed errors; avoid generic `Error` catches when possible
- Never force-unwrap (`!`) in production code; use `guard let` or `if let`
- Force-unwraps are acceptable in test code for known test data
- Throw meaningful errors with context; avoid `fatalError()` except for programmer errors

## Logging

- Use `os.Logger` for all logging:
  ```swift
  private let logger = Logger(subsystem: Bundle.main.bundleIdentifier!, category: "ModuleName")
  logger.info("Something happened")
  logger.error("Failed to load: \(error.localizedDescription)")
  ```
- Never use `print()` in production code
- Use appropriate log levels: `.debug`, `.info`, `.notice`, `.error`, `.fault`

## File Organization

- One primary type per file; file name matches type name
- Mirror source directory structure in test directory
- Group related files in directories matching feature/module boundaries
- Extensions on external types go in `Extensions/TypeName+Feature.swift`

## Accessibility

- All interactive elements must have `.accessibilityLabel`
- Decorative images: `.accessibilityHidden(true)`
- Group related elements with `.accessibilityElement(children: .combine)`
- Test with VoiceOver enabled before marking UI work complete

## Localization â€” Hard Gate

> **This is a BLOCKING rule, not a suggestion.** Every user-facing string MUST go through the localization system. Violations block merge.

### Rule

- **No hardcoded user-facing strings.** Every string shown to the user â€” window titles, button labels, menu items, tab titles, HUD messages, alert text, empty-state text, toggle labels, section headers, descriptions, tooltips â€” MUST use `String(localized:)` or `NSLocalizedString`.
- Include comments for translator context: `String(localized: "save_button", comment: "Button to save the current document")`

### What Counts as a Violation

Any bare string literal assigned to a UI-facing property. Examples:

```swift
// âťŚ VIOLATION â€” hardcoded user-facing strings
window.title = "Library"
segmentedControl.setLabel("All", forSegment: 0)
label.stringValue = "Cleanup Settings"
Text("Enable Auto Cleanup (Pro)")
Button("Delete") { ... }
cell.textField?.stringValue = "No items"
window.title = String(format: "%d images copied", count)

// âś… CORRECT â€” localized strings
window.title = String(localized: "library.window_title", comment: "Library window title")
segmentedControl.setLabel(String(localized: "library.filter_all", comment: "Filter: show all items"), forSegment: 0)
label.stringValue = String(localized: "cleanup.settings_title", comment: "Cleanup settings section header")
Text(String(localized: "cleanup.enable_auto_pro", comment: "Toggle label for auto cleanup pro feature"))
Button(String(localized: "action.delete", comment: "Delete button")) { ... }
```

### Exceptions (NOT violations)

- Internal log messages: `logger.info("Processing started")`
- Debug-only strings: `#if DEBUG` blocks
- String identifiers / keys (not shown to user): `UserDefaults.standard.string(forKey: "lastSync")`
- System API parameters: `NSPasteboard.PasteboardType("public.utf8-plain-text")`
- Accessibility identifiers (not labels): `.accessibilityIdentifier("deleteButton")`
- Brand names used as-is: `"Pro"` when it is a product tier name kept in English across all locales

### Mandatory Self-Check Before Completing Any UI Task

When writing or modifying ANY file that contains UI code (Views, Controllers, Windows, Panels, Menus, HUD, Alerts), you MUST:

1. **Scan every string literal** in the new/modified code
2. **For each string literal**, determine: is this shown to the user?
3. **If yes** â†’ it MUST use `String(localized:)` with a meaningful key and comment
4. **If yes but the key does not exist** in `en.lproj/Localizable.strings` â†’ add the key to ALL language files
5. **Never defer localization** â€” do NOT write `// TODO: localize` and move on. Localize now or the task is not complete.

## Sandbox and Entitlements

- Document any new entitlement additions in commit messages
- Use `NSOpenPanel` / `NSSavePanel` for user-selected file access
- Use security-scoped bookmarks for persistent file access
- Never request broader entitlements than needed
